Tableau: North Carolina Teacher Support Program & Duke Pratt School of Engineering Enrollment trends, study away

Soraya Campbell

2022-05-26

NC Teacher Support Program

  • Stakeholders wanted internal dashboard of KPIs of enrollment, demographic, and coaching support data
  • Task was to develop KPIs after EDA, create dashboard with associated visualizations
  • Collaborative, contract position through Friday Institute for Educational Innovation, NCSU

Data

  • Excel files extracted from internal database
  • Inputs are from more than 100 coaches throughout the state who collected data in the field
    • Each observation was an encounter on a specific date with a teacher enrolled in program
  • Notable - coaching support data were in columnar format with each support having multiple levels of data, which in turn needed multi-level pivoting

Cleaning: Tableau Prep

  • Because of the multi-level pivot, introduced Tableau Prep Builder to create two extracts of data for analysis

    • One focused on enrollment/demographic info

    • One focused on coaching supports

  • Data needed primary key (row id for each encounter; ‘row number’ function) and secondary key (email; created ‘dummy’ email for null values)

Exploratory Data Analysis

  • After exploring the data extensively via Prep, sought to capture KPIs dealing with time in program, types of supports most heavily used, modality of support, etc.

  • Analyses were presented in dashboards that was then organized into a Story

    • Use of color to differentiate focus of dashboards within Story

Key Insights

  • Most teachers in program for a year
  • More ‘rural’ counties have the worst retention rates
  • Most coaching supports consisted of observation and sharing of resources based on observations
  • Coaching encounters averaged out to ~40 mins
  • Gradual move to virtual encounters through 2019 shifted greatly in 2020 to majority virtual due to pandemic - trend has continued even after initial lockdowns, etc.

Pratt School of Engineering: Study Away

  • Tableau public dashboard
  • Duke has a higher than national average number of engineering/STEM students who study abroad
  • Analyzed trends in enrollment, destination, and demographic data
  • Interesting trends with female participation
  • Most engineering students favor English speaking destinations
